03:46.685 --> 03:49.935
[Tom] <i>Baltimore has always been</i>
<i>a quintessentially Catholic city.</i>

03:52.482 --> 03:54.742
<i>Baltimore is the home</i>
<i>of Roman Catholicism.</i>

03:55.819 --> 03:58.819
<i>John Carroll founded</i>
<i>the first archdiocese here,</i>

03:58.905 --> 04:00.905
<i>maybe the late 1700s.</i>

04:03.577 --> 04:06.457
[Deb] <i>Baltimore is a city of firsts.</i>

04:07.664 --> 04:09.004
<i>The first telegraph...</i>

04:11.001 --> 04:13.171
<i>the first streetlights...</i>

04:14.129 --> 04:15.169
<i>the trains.</i>

04:17.632 --> 04:21.642
<i>And it is the first diocese</i>
<i>in the United States.</i>

04:22.179 --> 04:26.809
<i>Every neighborhood had its own parish.</i>
<i>Everybody went to church.</i>

04:26.892 --> 04:28.602
<i>I mean, rosary,</i>

04:29.144 --> 04:31.484
<i>May processions were a big thing,</i>

04:31.897 --> 04:33.107
<i>First Communions.</i>

04:33.690 --> 04:36.490
<i>All the Sacraments were a really big deal.</i>

04:37.819 --> 04:42.739
You were not only going to school
with people that were Catholic,

04:42.824 --> 04:46.334
going to church with people Catholic,
you were living in Catholic communities.

04:48.330 --> 04:51.500
[Tom] <i>But Baltimore has always been</i>
<i>a working-class city.</i>

04:53.752 --> 04:56.712
<i>In 1969, when Sister Cathy dies,</i>

04:57.214 --> 05:02.394
<i>we lived in a much more basic,</i>
<i>simplistic, primitive society.</i>

05:04.262 --> 05:08.522
<i>This is a world of blue-collar folks,</i>
<i>they're working in these factory jobs.</i>

05:09.768 --> 05:12.148
<i>They are living in little row houses,</i>

05:12.229 --> 05:14.859
<i>they are tending</i>
<i>little postage-stamp lawns.</i>

05:15.565 --> 05:17.435
<i>They are living for that glorious moment</i>

05:17.526 --> 05:22.196
when their little daughter puts on a veil
and goes for her First Communion.

05:26.326 --> 05:28.786
[Jean] <i>I was one of ten siblings.</i>

05:29.162 --> 05:34.042
<i>There were three boys...</i>
<i>me, then three boys,</i>

05:34.501 --> 05:36.551
<i>then there were two girls and a boy.</i>

05:37.671 --> 05:41.131
It was a good Catholic family.
Eleven months later you had another baby.

05:46.054 --> 05:47.474
[inaudible]

05:54.062 --> 05:57.072
<i>My parents were good Catholic parents.</i>

05:58.608 --> 06:01.608
<i>Everybody went to church on Sunday,</i>

06:01.695 --> 06:05.155
<i>and if you didn't have a ride</i>
<i>because dad was a policeman</i>

06:05.240 --> 06:08.080
<i>and he worked shift work,</i>
<i>you'd walk to church.</i>

06:08.952 --> 06:10.292
[Ed] <i>You know, it was unheard of</i>

06:10.370 --> 06:15.580
to either miss church on Sunday
or eat meat on Friday.

06:15.667 --> 06:17.417
During the Cuban Missile Crisis,

06:17.502 --> 06:19.842
we all knelt down and said the rosary.

06:21.256 --> 06:24.676
<i>The Catholic religion, the Catholic faith</i>
<i>was part of who we were.</i>

06:29.055 --> 06:30.425
[Don] <i>We were all altar boys.</i>

06:31.308 --> 06:34.478
<i>We were told it was an honor</i>
<i>and a privilege to be an altar boy.</i>

06:36.896 --> 06:39.976
<i>The priests were the authority.</i>

06:40.984 --> 06:42.364
You don't question them.

06:42.444 --> 06:46.414
Uh, you-- You--
Whatever they told you to do, you did.

06:47.157 --> 06:48.327
[Ed] <i>My mom was very devout.</i>

06:48.408 --> 06:51.698
<i>It was an integral part of the family,</i>
<i>which came from her.</i>

06:52.245 --> 06:55.075
[Mike] <i>But my dad was there.</i>
<i>I mean, like, if we went to confession,</i>

06:55.498 --> 06:59.588
<i>it was nothing like seeing your father go</i>
<i>to confession first and then come out.</i>

06:59.669 --> 07:03.089
It was kind of like-- If he believed
and trusted the confessional,

07:03.173 --> 07:04.223
then we all did, too.

07:05.675 --> 07:09.425
[Bob] <i> My mother was, in fact,</i>
<i>a true Christian.</i>

07:10.263 --> 07:13.143
If you lived right and you loved God,

07:13.558 --> 07:15.228
<i>that faith that you exhibited,</i>

07:15.477 --> 07:18.227
<i>plus the love that you had</i>
<i>for your fellow man,</i>

07:18.647 --> 07:23.187
<i>would provide the hope that you need</i>
<i>in order to succeed.</i>

07:34.162 --> 07:36.162
[indistinct chatter over TV]

07:38.500 --> 07:39.920
Got you some cereal,

07:40.293 --> 07:44.763
put some strawberries on it today
instead of banana.

07:47.842 --> 07:50.802
-So, there's that, okay?
-Mm-hm.

07:50.887 --> 07:52.137
Your coffee.

07:53.473 --> 07:55.023
We'll let that cool a little bit.

07:56.017 --> 07:56.937
Alrighty?

08:09.698 --> 08:10.868
This is my senior.

08:12.075 --> 08:17.155
This was the end
of a pretty horrific experience.

08:17.539 --> 08:22.879
And I probably was relieved
that it was... ending.

08:24.921 --> 08:26.341
She holds memories,

08:26.423 --> 08:28.933
and I've been afraid of those memories.

08:37.392 --> 08:42.312
[Gemma] <i>Archbishop Keough was the jewel</i>
<i>in the archdiocese.</i>

08:43.398 --> 08:45.938
It was a really nice new school.

08:46.484 --> 08:50.414
<i>It had that spanking-new type</i>
<i>of, uh, look to it.</i>

08:51.489 --> 08:55.289
[Gemma] <i>Run by nuns,</i>
<i>the School Sisters of Notre Dame.</i>

08:56.870 --> 09:00.620
[Teresa] <i>It was really a big deal</i>
<i>to be accepted to go to Archbishop Keough.</i>

09:01.041 --> 09:03.501
You had to get in.
You had to take an entrance exam.

09:03.585 --> 09:06.545
So, the big day in eighth grade
would be when you came home for lunch

09:06.629 --> 09:10.799
and your letter was waiting for you
that you had been admitted to Keough.

09:11.885 --> 09:13.295
[Kathy] <i>It was prestigious.</i>

09:14.262 --> 09:16.772
I was very excited because that's exactly

09:16.848 --> 09:20.098
where I wanted to go. It was
within walking distance of my house.

09:20.810 --> 09:22.690
[Teresa] <i>I really was excited about going.</i>

09:22.771 --> 09:26.071
I remember my freshman year,
I was very, very happy to be there.

09:27.942 --> 09:31.492
My parents worked hard
that I could go to it.

09:32.822 --> 09:34.702
[Deb] <i>It was very exciting...</i>

09:35.408 --> 09:37.038
but really strict.

09:38.286 --> 09:40.656
<i>There was order, discipline.</i>

09:40.955 --> 09:44.745
You know, you had nuns all over the place.
There were a lot of nuns.

09:47.462 --> 09:52.262
[Gemma] <i>Our administrators were nuns,</i>
<i>our principal, our assistant principal.</i>

09:53.384 --> 09:55.514
<i>Joseph Maskell was the chaplain.</i>

09:57.180 --> 10:02.560
<i>There was also a priest</i>
<i>by the name of Father Neil Magnus.</i>

10:03.019 --> 10:07.819
-He was responsible for studies or...
-Christian education or something--

10:07.899 --> 10:10.359
I never saw the man, that I remember.

10:20.537 --> 10:24.997
[Teresa] <i>They had language labs</i>
<i>and really state-of-the-art equipment.</i>

10:25.542 --> 10:27.712
[Donna] <i>They had a science room.</i>

10:28.670 --> 10:30.550
[Gemma] <i>They had a large gym.</i>

10:30.630 --> 10:34.470
<i>It had a large outdoor field</i>
<i>for different sports.</i>

10:35.677 --> 10:39.677
[Teresa] <i>They even put</i>
<i>"we are women of a new age" in their song,</i>

10:40.014 --> 10:44.644
and it was just supposed to be women
being able to reach their full potential.

10:44.727 --> 10:46.517
It was supposed to be a safe place.

10:53.611 --> 10:57.241
My life would have been very different
if I had not gone in that confessional.

11:02.704 --> 11:03.914
<i>I was at Keough.</i>

11:03.997 --> 11:05.117
<i>I was a freshman.</i>

11:07.208 --> 11:09.538
<i>I went to confession there.</i>

11:12.964 --> 11:15.684
<i>It took me five tries</i>
<i>to get to the confessional.</i>

11:19.304 --> 11:20.814
<i>I got in the confessional...</i>

11:21.389 --> 11:26.689
<i>and I told the priest something</i>
<i>that I was feeling very guilty about.</i>

11:29.272 --> 11:32.402
<i>I had been abused by an uncle</i>
<i>when I was younger.</i>

11:33.443 --> 11:37.953
He was a pedophile
and he was sexually abusing me.

11:39.240 --> 11:42.040
<i>That had ended, there was some guilt.</i>

11:43.995 --> 11:48.075
<i>And I always remembered it was Magnus</i>
<i>and always remembered that he said:</i>

11:48.791 --> 11:50.881
"Can I look at you,
and what is your name?"

11:52.503 --> 11:55.473
<i>And I always thought,</i>
<i>"God, this must have been so terrible</i>

11:55.548 --> 11:57.718
that he had to look at me
and ask my name."

11:59.636 --> 12:01.886
<i>And at the end of it he said:</i>

12:01.971 --> 12:04.521
<i>"I don't really know</i>
<i>if God can forgive this.</i>

12:05.058 --> 12:08.388
<i>I'm going to have to pray more on this</i>
<i>and I'll get back to you."</i>

12:21.240 --> 12:24.950
<i>Probably a couple weeks later,</i>
<i>the same priest, Magnus,</i>

12:25.036 --> 12:26.656
<i>walked up to me in the hall...</i>

12:27.705 --> 12:30.495
<i>and he said</i>
<i>he wanted to see me in his office.</i>

12:35.296 --> 12:37.546
<i>And Magnus was there...</i>

12:37.924 --> 12:42.264
<i>and he proceeded to just reiterate</i>
<i>that I was so bad...</i>

12:42.679 --> 12:48.939
that it was going to take a while
before there was going to be a real answer

12:49.018 --> 12:50.688
to whether God could forgive me.

12:52.605 --> 12:57.355
<i>And that if I emptied myself</i>
<i>of these behaviors</i>

12:57.443 --> 13:00.453
<i>that were so sinful, so bad...</i>

13:00.989 --> 13:02.529
<i>that it would make room for God</i>

13:02.615 --> 13:05.695
<i>to be able to fill me</i>
<i>with the Holy Spirit...</i>

13:06.369 --> 13:08.619
<i>and that I could be forgiven.</i>

13:09.706 --> 13:12.876
The things that he was doing
was "sacramental,"

13:12.959 --> 13:14.129
you know, quote-unquote.

13:14.585 --> 13:15.495
Um...

13:15.586 --> 13:22.046
That, you know, he talked about, uh,
his come as the Eucharist, you know.

13:22.135 --> 13:26.925
He was doing symbols on me
of the crucifix with it

13:27.015 --> 13:29.635
as if it was, uh, sacred.

13:30.143 --> 13:35.313
He was also saying that his come was
the Holy Spirit that I was to swallow.

13:36.899 --> 13:38.399
<i>I was very naive.</i>

13:39.110 --> 13:40.860
<i>I was extremely innocent.</i>

13:41.446 --> 13:46.616
I had no idea
that this was, um, abusive.

13:46.701 --> 13:50.751
I felt that it was a man of...

13:51.039 --> 13:53.789
Of authority, of faith,

13:53.875 --> 13:59.005
who was helping me become a good person.

14:00.006 --> 14:05.506
He was reminding me
that the things that I had done were--

14:05.595 --> 14:08.255
weren't done to me.
That I made those things happen.

14:11.309 --> 14:15.729
<i>After a couple of my therapy sessions</i>
<i>with him,</i>

14:15.813 --> 14:17.443
<i>I went into the room...</i>

14:18.441 --> 14:20.741
<i>and then Maskell came in.</i>

14:23.863 --> 14:26.373
<i>From the beginning,</i>
<i>I was afraid of Maskell.</i>

14:26.657 --> 14:29.617
<i>He had no qualms being angry with me.</i>

14:30.036 --> 14:32.956
<i>He started very early on</i>
<i>calling me a whore.</i>

14:35.041 --> 14:39.881
They would pray in Latin over me
as they were having me do things to them,

14:39.962 --> 14:42.342
or they were doing things to me.

14:42.423 --> 14:44.973
Or one would be praying over me in Latin

14:45.051 --> 14:48.261
while the other one would be,
you know, kind of saying:

14:48.346 --> 14:52.176
"Take the Holy Spirit," and, um--
You know, through his penis.

14:53.810 --> 14:57.560
<i>So, it is a very interesting dynamic</i>
<i>to feel both of them in the room,</i>

14:57.647 --> 14:58.977
<i>to be cornered by them both,</i>

14:59.065 --> 15:04.695
<i>to feel two men of not only great size,</i>

15:05.071 --> 15:09.161
<i>but that they were powerful</i>
<i>because they represented God.</i>

15:11.119 --> 15:14.159
I-- I wanted to get out of that room,

15:14.622 --> 15:18.632
and yet I felt that
I had to be in the room in order to...

15:19.293 --> 15:21.923
to... be a good person.

15:22.630 --> 15:27.090
It was-- It was the beginning
of some of the thickest confusion

15:27.510 --> 15:30.430
that, um, probably could be imagined.

15:35.643 --> 15:37.403
<i>At a particular point...</i>

15:38.187 --> 15:42.687
<i>I went to the room</i>
<i>and it was just Maskell there.</i>

15:43.526 --> 15:45.446
<i>And it was a very scary point.</i>

15:47.947 --> 15:52.447
<i>He was angry at me</i>
<i>because I wasn't getting better.</i>

15:53.995 --> 15:58.455
I remember one time he was real angry
and he was raping me.

15:58.541 --> 16:02.341
And I can remember
my head hitting the... the wall.

16:04.839 --> 16:07.339
<i>He was really upset and angry</i>
<i>about something...</i>

16:07.758 --> 16:10.338
<i>and he was really taking it out on me.</i>

16:12.388 --> 16:14.468
I couldn't figure out what I could do

16:14.557 --> 16:17.727
because I kept feeling
like every time it was over, I thought:

16:17.810 --> 16:19.810
"Well, maybe this time God forgave me."

16:23.441 --> 16:28.071
[Deb] <i>I had never been in a school</i>
<i>where a priest had a presence</i>

16:28.154 --> 16:31.784
<i>like the priests had there,</i>
<i>because they had offices at Keough.</i>

16:33.117 --> 16:36.367
Father Maskell wielded a lot of power

16:36.621 --> 16:39.371
and fear in people

16:39.457 --> 16:42.537
because you didn't wanna be called
to his office or get in trouble.

16:43.336 --> 16:47.086
[Lil] <i>He was chaplain</i>
<i>and school counselor at Keough.</i>

16:48.674 --> 16:51.014
The building itself was a very long...

16:51.093 --> 16:55.473
<i>rectangle with some corridors</i>
<i>that went off in different directions.</i>

16:55.806 --> 17:00.136
<i>And his office was far</i>
<i>from the administrative offices.</i>

17:00.228 --> 17:03.898
<i>He was down at the far corner</i>
<i>where there was an exit.</i>

17:04.690 --> 17:08.069
You used to see a lot of girls
coming in and out of his office,

17:08.152 --> 17:10.202
which was kind of strange.

17:10.279 --> 17:11.819
But then I learned that:

17:11.906 --> 17:12.906
"Hey, you know what?

17:12.990 --> 17:16.490
If you wanna smoke, you-- You can go
in Maskell's office and smoke.

17:16.577 --> 17:18.867
Just go in there, talk to him,
just hang out and talk."

17:20.873 --> 17:22.542
[Tom] <i>Maskell was an Irish priest</i>

17:22.625 --> 17:27.954
<i>right out of the traditional</i>
<i>working-class Irish-American community.</i>

17:29.048 --> 17:33.008
His mother often dressed her boy
in Mass vestments.

17:33.094 --> 17:35.934
She used to sew him vestments
and he'd dress up in them and--

17:36.013 --> 17:36.853
Mm-hm.

17:36.931 --> 17:39.061
--call the neighborhood kids over
to say Mass for them.

17:40.309 --> 17:44.809
She went and bought NECCO Wafers
and she segregated the white ones out

17:44.897 --> 17:48.937
so that they could serve
as imitation hosts for Communion.

17:49.527 --> 17:52.027
<i>While the other boys were playing</i>
<i>football and baseball</i>

17:52.113 --> 17:54.283
<i>down two blocks away at the park...</i>

17:56.784 --> 17:58.624
he would say Mass in the yard.

17:58.703 --> 18:00.713
[man speaking in Latin]

18:01.372 --> 18:04.792
[Tom] <i>From 15 years old,</i>
<i>he was priest-in-training.</i>

18:07.670 --> 18:10.090
[Abbie] <i>In '65, he was ordained.</i>

18:11.716 --> 18:15.596
And then his first assignment
from 1965 to 1966

18:16.178 --> 18:19.178
<i>was at a Baltimore parish</i>
<i>named Sacred Heart of Mary.</i>

18:21.142 --> 18:26.612
<i>In '66, he was transferred</i>
<i>to St. Clement Parish, which is adjacent</i>

18:26.689 --> 18:28.769
<i>to Archbishop Keough High School.</i>

18:29.942 --> 18:32.452
He was made associate pastor there.

18:34.822 --> 18:37.032
And he supervised
the Boy Scout troop there.

18:51.672 --> 18:52.972
This is my, uh...

18:54.342 --> 18:57.472
I guess--
My wife calls it a dust collection room.

18:59.513 --> 19:02.313
That was my retirement certificate.

19:04.185 --> 19:06.515
There's my grandfather.
The great-great-grandfather

19:06.604 --> 19:09.944
I was telling you about,
Southern District policeman in Baltimore,

19:10.024 --> 19:11.984
and there's a picture of him later.

19:13.944 --> 19:16.364
Me and my brother worked

19:16.447 --> 19:18.697
in the police station
he worked out of, so...

19:19.408 --> 19:20.908
Kind of like family tradition.

19:25.998 --> 19:30.798
<i>When I started Catholic school</i>
<i>in the early '60s,</i>

19:30.878 --> 19:32.508
<i>it was a pretty harsh environment.</i>

19:33.631 --> 19:34.631
We were paddled.

19:34.715 --> 19:38.755
I mean, the nuns--
We feared the nuns and--

19:39.011 --> 19:43.061
Not only the nuns, but the priests,
they were on a whole different level.

19:43.140 --> 19:47.560
The priests were...
more like godlike figures, and...

19:48.229 --> 19:52.569
I mean, they'd walk in the room,
it'd just be silence, and, um...

19:52.650 --> 19:56.200
<i>But this priest, Father Joseph Maskell,</i>
<i>there was something about him.</i>

19:56.737 --> 20:00.197
<i>He had a... </i> [sighs] <i> coldness about him.</i>

20:00.741 --> 20:03.291
<i>And I've served Mass</i>
<i>for different priests.</i>

20:04.662 --> 20:08.292
<i>And one day,</i>
<i>we were getting ready for Mass--</i>

20:08.374 --> 20:11.004
<i>You know, the altar boys,</i>
<i>we'd get there a little early.</i>

20:11.085 --> 20:13.335
<i>He'd come into the sacristy and, um...</i>

20:14.422 --> 20:17.302
He takes a handgun out of his pocket
and put it on the...

20:17.383 --> 20:18.803
<i>the counter in the sacristy.</i>

20:19.176 --> 20:22.006
<i>And being a street-smart kid,</i>
<i>you know, from the city,</i>

20:22.555 --> 20:25.265
<i>growing up watching </i> Adam-12
<i>and things like that, I mean...</i>

20:27.268 --> 20:30.518
<i>Probably most kids</i>
<i>wouldn't have questioned him, but...</i>

20:31.230 --> 20:32.190
<i>I just let it go.</i>

